'''Charles Edward Anton''' (1860 – 16 November 1935) was a Scottish businessman who was the 16th [[tai-pan]] of the [[Jardine, Matheson & Co.]] and a member of the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].

==Biography==
Anton was born in [[St Pancras, London]],<ref>''England & Wales, Civil Registration Birth Index, 1837-1915''</ref> to Scottish parents George Anton, a merchant, and Mary Lindsay.<ref>''1871 Scotland Census''</ref> He joined the [[Jardine, Matheson & Co.]] in 1884 and spent some time in the Shanghai office. He was authorised to sign ''per pro'' in 1904. In 1910, he was appointed a director and eventually retired in 1919. During 1917 when he was the director of Jardine he was also member of the [[Hong Kong General Chamber of Commerce]] and the [[Legislative Council of Hong Kong]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Obituary.|newspaper=The China Mail|date=19 November 1935}}</ref>

Anton died of pneumonia at [[Broughty Ferry]], [[Dundee]], Scotland on 16 November 1935, leaving local estate sworn under £225,500 (£{{formatprice|{{Inflation|UK|225501|1935|r=-1}}|0}} as of {{CURRENTYEAR}}).<ref>{{cite news|title=Local Estate.|newspaper=The China Mail|date=19 May 1936|page=12}}</ref>

==Memory==
Anton Street ({{zh|t=晏頓街}}) in [[Wan Chai]] was named after him.<ref>{{cite book |title=Signs of a Colonial Era |date=2009 |publisher=Hong Kong University Press |isbn=9789622099449 |page=97 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=DpOQrEVBcX4C&pg=PA97&dq=%22Charles+Edward+Anton%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwi6nYrLnNnbAhUkw4MKHbDQAFwQ6AEINDAC#v=onepage&q=%22Charles%20Edward%22%20Anton&f=false |accessdate=16 June 2018 |language=en}}</ref>

